instances.text: FREN_V 311-201 - Introduction to Literature in French

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Critical reading of foundational literary texts in French from genres of prose fiction, non-fiction, poetry, and theatre.
View full course overview:https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/fren311/ 

Language of instruction: French

If you are a native French speaker, bilingual, completed French Immersion 12, or graduated from a Francophone school, we can manually register you. Please send your request here: https://fhis.ubc.ca/undergraduate-advising-contact-form/

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
FREN 321 provides advanced training in writing a variety of types of papers in French with emphasis placed on writing that requires the student to think critically and creatively, support generalizations, and appropriately acknowledge sources of information, which is particularly relevant given the rise of AI tools.
If you are a native French speaker, bilingual, completed French Immersion 12, or graduated from a Francophone school, we can manually register you. Please send your request here: https://fhis.ubc.ca/undergraduate-advising-contact-form/

View full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/fren321/

Language of instruction: French

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Rues, routes et boulevards: Modern Narratives in French : This class will focus on literary representations of Paris and Nature, as means to grasp the evolution of French literature from the early nineteenth to the present. We will read major authors who situated their narratives in revolutions, wars, and other moments of artistic or historic upheaval. 
View full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/fren341/ 

Language of instruction: French

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
The most advanced grammar course in the program. Strengthen your autonomy, analyze a series of relevant grammatical issues (articles, relative pronouns, agreement, verb tenses, etc.) and think critically about French language. Aligned with CEFR levels C1-C2 objectives.
View full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/fren353/

Language of instruction: French

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Principles, practical strategies and methods of translation from French to English and English to French. Overview of the main challenges involved in intercultural communication.
View full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/fren357/

Language of instruction: French
